NOTES ON SPECIAL MOUSE MODE:
 Normally, the "PC2" side of the Smart Port is either "ANALOG" (LIGHT
 ILLUMINATED) or "DIGITAL" (LIGHT NOT ILLUMINATED). However, there is a hybrid
 mode called "SPECIAL MOUSE MODE" which is enabled by switching the mouse mode
 switch away from the 15-pin connector. In this case, you are converting the
 middle mouse button into an analog input.  All other digital mouse functions
 will be unaffected.  This allows you to activate ONE analog line while the
 mouse is still available.  This is VERY useful if your hardware does not
 have a button available to put the port in full analog mode.  With this feature
 the built-in throttle on the CH FlightStick (and others) can be used.  This is
 the mode Fighter Duel Pro uses to provide rudder capability.


******************************************************************************
* FA-18 Interceptor - DETAILED PRE-FLIGHT CHECK LIST (after entering cockpit)*
*               Performed on start-up or as needed.                          *
* It is recommended that these procedures be preformed before take off.      *
******************************************************************************
 The following instructions describe various configurations for several
 combinations of hardware.  Locate the appropriate combination for your
 particular situation.

IMPORTANT: NO analog functions will work correctly, unless the light labeled
           "PC1" on the AMIGA Smart Port is illuminated. In addition, the analog
           throttle and the analog pedals will not function if the indicator
           light labeled "PC2" on the AMIGA Smart Port is not illuminated.
           Unless the special mouse mode switch is engaged.

IMPORTANT: At the beginning of the session, the center and full scale
           for each analog device must be initialized at least once
           For more information, see the detailed description below.
           This can be repeated as often as necessary.

WARNING:   Pressing the digital joystick "FIRE" button will deactivate "ALL"
           analog functions ("PC1" light not illuminated).  Press the analog
           joystick "FIRE" button to restore the analog functions ("PC1" light
           illuminated).

           Pressing the left mouse button ("PC2" light not illuminated) will
           deactivate the mouse port one analog mode.  Functions such as pedals,
           analog rudder, buttons 3&4, and "HAT" switch will not operate
           properly under these conditions.  To restore the "PC2" functions,
           perform one of the methods in Step 3 of "USING THE ANALOG PEDALS"
           described below.


USING THE ANALOG JOYSTICK:
1. Connect an analog joystick to the AMIGA Smart Port.
2. Place Port 2 of the Amiga Smart Port in analog mode by pressing the analog
   joystick "FIRE" button.
3. The "PC 1" light on the AMIGA Smart Port should be illuminated.
4. Make sure the analog joystick is in the center, then press the "L" key to
   set the center point.
5. Move the joystick to all four corners of travel to set maximum scale.
6. If you want a different sensitivity than the default (HIGH/5),
   select it at any time by performing the following:
   A. Hold down the Left AMIGA Key and press the "L" key for the high
      sensitivity joystick range (DEFAULT) or the Right AMIGA key and the "L"
      key for the low sensitivity range.  Try experimenting as you fly!
   B. Fine tune the sensitivity by holding down the SHIFT (for the Roll axis)
      or Left AMIGA (for the pitch axis) key and pressing a numeric key on the
      main keyboard.   Left to right on the keyboard:
            1 = (lowest sensitivity) to   0 = (highest sensitivity).
      Be sure to hold down the shift or left AMIGA key BEFORE you press the
      numeric key.    Try experimenting while your flying!
   This provides 10 settings per range. Using both ranges yields 20
   settings per axis.
7. If you want a different center "DEAD" zone than the default, select it at
   any time by pressing the "U" key alone or any one of the following keys
   {SHIFT, LEFT AMIGA, RIGHT AMIGA} with the "U" key.
   The best center "DEAD" zone is determined by the centering accuracy of your
   joystick, and your personal preferences.
(See "DEAD" Zone Description below)


USING THE ANALOG RUDDER PEDALS:
1. Attach one of the following combinations to the AMIGA Smart Port:
    A. Aircraft pedals and a standard analog joystick connected
       via an Advanced Game Port Adapter (from IDD).
       NOTE: The Advanced Game Port Adapter is necessary if your joystick
             does not incorporate at least three buttons.
       Both switches on the Game Port Adapter should be switched to "NORMAL".
    B. IDD'S PC PEDALS(TM) and a standard analog joystick.
    C. An analog joystick with a second analog joystick (for use as pedals)
       using a standard IBM "Y" adapter cable (Available from IDD).
    D. Aircraft pedals and a standard analog joystick connected
       via the original Rudder Pedal Adapter (no longer available from IDD).
       In addition you MUST use the "Y" key on the keyboard to set the rudder/
       throttle inputs to "REVERSE". Also the "Special Mouse Mode Switch" on
       the AMIGA Smart Port MUST be switched away from the 15 pin connecter.
2. Perform the steps under "USING THE ANALOG JOYSTICK".

   IF YOU ARE USING A RUDDER PEDAL ADAPTER, SKIP TO STEP 5.

3. Place Port 1 of the Amiga Smart Port in analog mode, using ONE of the
   following methods:
   (If none apply to you, then you do not have the proper hardware)
   A. Press button 3 on your joystick if it has extra buttons. Button 3 is
      simply the button that turns on the AMIGA Smart Port "PC 2" light.
   B. If you have the Advanced Game Port Adapter (from IDD), enable the
      "PC 2" Trigger Switch. Press the second button on the analog
      joystick.  The "PC 2" light on AMIGA Smart Port should now be on.
   C. If you are using two joysticks with a "Y" cable (available from IDD),
      press the "fire" button on the second analog joystick.
      The "PC 2" light on AMIGA Smart Port should now be on.
   D. Press the mode select button on the IDD PC Pedals... available December
      1993 from IDD.
4. The "PC 2" light on the AMIGA Smart Port "MUST" now be on.
5. Make sure the analog pedals are in the mechanical center, then press the "Q"
   key to set the center point.
6. To set the full scale, push the left pedal to the maximum travel, then
   push the right pedal to the maximum travel.
7. If you want a different sensitivity than the default (HIGH/5),
   select it at any time by performing the following:
   A. Hold down the Left AMIGA Key and press the "Q" key for the High
      sensitivity pedal range (DEFAULT) or the Right AMIGA key and the "Q"
      key for the Low sensitivity range.
      Try experimenting while you are flying!
   B. Fine tune the sensitivity by holding down the Right AMIGA key and
      pressing a numeric key on the main keyboard.
      Left to right on the keyboard:
      1 = (lowest sensitivity) to   0=(highest sensitivity). Be sure to hold
        down the right AMIGA key BEFORE you press the numeric key.
      Try experimenting while you are flying!
   This provides you with 10 settings per range. Using both ranges yields 20
   settings.
8. If you want a different center "DEAD" zone than the default, select it at
   any time by pressing the "I" key alone or any one of the following
   {SHIFT, LEFT AMIGA, RIGHT AMIGA} with the "I" key.
   The best center "DEAD" zone is determined by the centering accuracy of
   your pedals and your personal preferences.
   (See "DEAD" zone description below)


USING THE ANALOG Throttle:
1. Attach one of the following combinations to the AMIGA Smart Port:
   A. Two analog joysticks using a standard IBM "Y" adapter cable.
      (Available from IDD)
   B. Two analog joysticks connected via the PC PEDALS(TM) [BY IDD].
   C. An analog joystick with built-in throttle, using either the
      Advanced Game Port Adapter or the PC PEDALS(TM) [Both from IDD].
   D. An analog joystick with built-in throttle.
      (With this option, the "Special Mouse Mode" switch on the AMIGA Smart
      Port can be switched away from the 15-pin connecter to activate the
      built-in throttle.
   NOTE: Any device used for throttle should NOT be self-centering.
2. Initialize the joystick by performing the steps under "USING THE ANALOG
   JOYSTICK".

   IF THE "SPECIAL MOUSE MODE" SWITCH IS ENABLED(TOWARD THE 15 PIN CONNECTOR),
   SKIP TO STEP 5.

3. Activate the analog mode on Port 1 ("PC2" light illuminated) of the Amiga
   Smart Port by any of the three methods described in step 3 of "USING THE
   ANALOG RUDDER".
4. The "PC1" and "PC2" indicator lights "MUST" be illuminated.
5. Press the "K" key to activate the throttle.
6. Move the device used for throttle to maximum range in both directions.
   WARNING!!!  Be quick or the aircraft will take off!


USING BUTTONS 3 AND 4 FUNCTIONS:
1. Connect a joystick with extra buttons to the AMIGA Smart Port.
2. Activate the analog mode of Port 1 ("PC2" light illuminated) of the Amiga
   Smart Port by any of the three methods described in step 3 of "USING THE
   ANALOG RUDDER PEDALS".
3. Press the "W" key to activate the buttons.

OPTIONAL:  If you are using a CH FlightStick PRO, press the "DEL" key to toggle
           between the viewing mode styles.


CENTER "DEAD" ZONE DESCRIPTION:
  The center "DEAD" zone is an artificially extended area around the center
  point of the joystick or pedals which the software interprets as center or
  null.  This allows for variations in the precision of the centering return
  mechanism of the joystick or pedals.
  Simple rule... If the center drifts, try a less sensitive setting.
        ("NARROW" = Most Sensitive / "WIDE" = least Sensitive)
  If you like to make very small corrections, you may want to select the most
  sensitive setting for your joystick.  Otherwise, accept the default or use
  the WIDE setting.  There are many parameters which affect the mechanical and
  electrical characteristics of your joystick and pedals.  Experiment with the
  various combinations of joystick and software settings to fit your
  preferences.

